_...What is the purpose of this_...  
  
For context in understanding what this code snippet can be used for, take a look at _[this link](http://www.pixelbeat.org/programming/stdio_buffering/)_ discussing stdio buffering.
In simplest logical terms, this technique consumes content placed in _[stdin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_streams)_ until the `newline` character is seen. (From a user hitting the `&lt;enter&gt;` key.)  This is evidently the lesson.   
This effectively clears the `stdin` buffer of content, also described _[in this more robust example](https://stackoverflow.com/a/36723075/645128)_.     
 

_Also what does_   

&gt; &quot;the following loop will read and ignore all remaining characters in
&gt; the current input line&quot;

 _mean actually?_

    do {
        scanf(&quot;%c&quot;, &amp;ch);
    } while (ch != &#39;\n&#39;);


It means that if the new `char` just read by `scanf` is not equal to the newline character, defined as `\n`, it will continue to overwrite `c` with the next read.  Once `ch` does equal `\n`, the loop will exit.

